- Oh, my Goodness, I'd forgotten.

10:01.020 --> 10:03.223
I'm supposed to meet my father at noon.

10:03.389 --> 10:05.155
Why don't we finish packing up here

10:05.275 --> 10:06.763
and regroup after lunch?

10:06.788 --> 10:07.890
Um...

10:07.915 --> 10:09.982
What are we going to do
with Eleanor's potato?

10:10.007 --> 10:11.806
Oh, well, we can...

10:11.831 --> 10:13.631
Can I keep it?

10:14.588 --> 10:16.388
Norman, we were simply tasked

10:16.413 --> 10:19.121
with clearing and retaining
postal-related items.

10:19.548 --> 10:21.014
Shane got a blender.

10:21.039 --> 10:22.970
Well, yes, but that's not...

10:22.995 --> 10:24.876
We'll take very good care of it.

10:24.901 --> 10:26.468
Those things are

10:26.493 --> 10:28.093
so untidy,

10:28.118 --> 10:31.853
and, uh, if left untended,
they produce an odor,

10:31.878 --> 10:34.120
that regulations clearly state...

10:34.145 --> 10:36.395
I will change the water
every day, I promise.

10:37.274 --> 10:38.640
Please?

10:38.665 --> 10:41.167
Just look at these little faces.

10:53.480 --> 10:55.937
- [Rita]: What do you think?
- Oh, dear.

10:56.754 --> 10:58.724
You think there's enough light here?

10:58.844 --> 11:01.054
Just think of it as a pet rock

11:01.079 --> 11:03.470
with the potential to be a side dish.

11:03.590 --> 11:06.182
They've already named it Charlene.

11:06.207 --> 11:08.202
- Oh.
- What about over here?

11:08.322 --> 11:10.189
That's a good sign, actually.

11:10.214 --> 11:11.480
How so, Ms. Mclnerney?

11:11.505 --> 11:14.025
[Quietly] Well... They're
not ready to formally take

11:14.145 --> 11:15.955
the next step in their relationship,

11:15.980 --> 11:17.313
so they've found a way

11:17.338 --> 11:19.810
to create a sort of
family with a surrogate...

11:20.493 --> 11:22.277
Potato.

11:22.302 --> 11:24.264
I really need to leave now.

11:24.384 --> 11:26.150
Okay, say hi to your dad for me.

11:26.175 --> 11:28.750
Oh, and, um... Oliver?

11:30.616 --> 11:34.485
I see that we're back to
saying "Ms. Mclnerney."

11:35.122 --> 11:36.621
Yes, uh, well...

11:38.625 --> 11:41.059
I think it might be more
important than ever

11:41.084 --> 11:44.232
to keep things... professional at work.

11:44.257 --> 11:46.654
But come tomorrow night, I fully intend

11:46.774 --> 11:48.368
to call you Shane...

11:50.037 --> 11:51.309
Ms. Mclnerney.

12:08.535 --> 12:09.634
Dad!

12:09.659 --> 12:10.758
Hey!

12:11.058 --> 12:13.458
Welcome to my retirement!

12:13.678 --> 12:15.144
Oh, uh...

12:15.929 --> 12:17.295
[Laughs]

12:18.236 --> 12:19.688
I wanted to talk about something.

12:20.052 --> 12:21.305
You know, I wrote that list

12:21.330 --> 12:23.430
of things I wanted to do when I retired.

12:23.455 --> 12:25.355
Travel, learn Italian,

12:25.380 --> 12:27.047
work in a garden.

12:27.374 --> 12:28.685
Uh...

12:28.989 --> 12:30.388
And then I realized

12:30.413 --> 12:31.912
that those things
would be a lot more fun

12:31.937 --> 12:34.738
if I didn't do them by myself.

12:34.763 --> 12:36.362
Oh, well, naturally.

12:36.387 --> 12:38.820
I'm not much of a
gardener, it's very messy,

12:38.845 --> 12:40.511
but I do love to travel, of course...

12:40.536 --> 12:43.286
I'm talking about needing some...

12:43.406 --> 12:45.829
- Company.
- Mm-hmm.

12:45.854 --> 12:46.920
Female company.

12:48.217 --> 12:49.428
Oh.

12:49.453 --> 12:53.159
I-I dated a little, you know,
after your mother left us,

12:53.279 --> 12:54.557
but nothing serious.

12:54.582 --> 12:57.550
But now I'm settled here, and, uh...

12:57.689 --> 12:59.371
I may not be old yet,

12:59.396 --> 13:01.196
but I will be someday.

13:01.221 --> 13:02.654
I don't want to do it alone.

13:02.679 --> 13:03.747
I see.

13:03.772 --> 13:07.634
Well, uh, there is a
book club at my church,

13:07.659 --> 13:10.847
- or we could find a seniors' group...
- Or I could just...

13:10.967 --> 13:13.868
Walk over to Kate and
ask her out right now.

13:15.719 --> 13:16.806
Kate.

13:17.001 --> 13:18.734
She's, uh...

13:18.759 --> 13:21.328
In charge of the butterfly garden,
and I'm handling the vegetables.

13:21.448 --> 13:23.949
And you are telling me this because...

13:23.974 --> 13:26.207
Well, let's face it,

13:26.232 --> 13:28.594
- we're different people.
- Mm-hmm.

13:28.714 --> 13:31.548
When I make a decision, I act.

13:32.762 --> 13:35.211
And I know you don't
like to rush things,

13:35.236 --> 13:38.103
and it's taken you a while to
get things going with Shane,

13:38.223 --> 13:40.947
and so I just, I don't want
you to feel awkward

13:40.972 --> 13:42.539
if I actually...

13:42.892 --> 13:44.859
Move a little faster than you.

13:44.884 --> 13:46.884
[Laughing] Well...

13:46.909 --> 13:51.230
Dad, Shane and I are
going out tomorrow, so...

13:51.255 --> 13:53.040
Well, there you go.

13:53.160 --> 13:54.453
That's great.

13:54.573 --> 13:56.673
Yeah. Okay.

13:56.957 --> 13:58.891
Nothin' to worry about then.

13:58.916 --> 14:00.206
[Chuckles]

14:01.939 --> 14:03.939
Well, she could be an "Irish cobbler,"

14:03.964 --> 14:06.431
or a "chieftain"... Ooh, or a "viking."

14:06.456 --> 14:09.824
She's definitely some sort
of early variety of heirloom.

14:09.849 --> 14:12.451
She's definitely not
your average potato.

14:12.476 --> 14:14.009
- Nope.
- Listen to this.

14:14.034 --> 14:15.481
Almost 400,000 people

14:15.506 --> 14:17.709
evacuated New Orleans
when the levees broke.

14:17.734 --> 14:19.643
And a lot of them are
still living in Colorado,

14:19.668 --> 14:21.835
because they can't
afford to move back home.

14:21.860 --> 14:23.490
Or they didn't have
a home to go back to.

14:23.515 --> 14:25.583
I wonder if that's what
happened to Gabe.

14:25.608 --> 14:27.241
[Door opens] I'm back, everyone.

14:27.266 --> 14:28.668
Sorry to keep you waiting.

14:28.693 --> 14:30.259
Hey, how's your dad?

14:30.284 --> 14:31.316
He's fine.

14:31.341 --> 14:33.167
Doing some volunteer work.

14:33.192 --> 14:36.493
Making new, uh, friends.

14:36.518 --> 14:39.244
I thought we might get
back to, uh, that letter.

14:39.269 --> 14:40.970
Oh, Shane's already got started on Gabe,

14:40.995 --> 14:42.279
and we've been working on Hattie.

14:42.376 --> 14:44.286
Yeah, I can't lift the
ink from the envelope

14:44.311 --> 14:45.843
without erasing Hattie's address.

14:45.868 --> 14:47.934
We even tried "Norman
Dorman's revelation solution."

14:47.959 --> 14:50.581
We might want to start going back
through some old phone books.

14:50.701 --> 14:51.782
Okay.

14:52.393 --> 14:53.459
Ms. Mclnerney?

14:53.484 --> 14:55.017
It's not looking good.

14:55.042 --> 14:56.976
All we've got is some guy named Gabe,

14:57.001 --> 14:59.001
who walked into some
sort of establishment,

14:59.026 --> 15:00.526
like a blues club,

15:00.551 --> 15:02.223
and sang a song, and had a good meal.

15:02.343 --> 15:03.643
And fell in love.

15:03.668 --> 15:06.308
- You think so?
- Oh, well, uh, where were we?

15:06.428 --> 15:07.527
Oh...

15:07.552 --> 15:09.185
"I'd always had the music in me,

15:09.210 --> 15:11.477
"but I'd forgotten what
it was for until you."

15:11.502 --> 15:13.190
He's obviously falling in love.

15:13.310 --> 15:14.630
Well, not necessarily.

15:14.655 --> 15:16.110
I mean, maybe he just thought

15:16.135 --> 15:17.601
she was being really encouraging.

15:17.626 --> 15:18.848
Well, I disagree.

15:18.873 --> 15:19.887
Uh...

15:19.912 --> 15:21.555
"I know what will keep me going.

15:21.675 --> 15:22.918
"Remembering you."

15:23.571 --> 15:26.446
If Gabe wrote one love letter,
maybe he wrote more,

15:26.471 --> 15:28.394
hoping one of them might get through

15:28.419 --> 15:29.956
all the chaos after Katrina.

15:29.981 --> 15:32.314
And if Hattie received
just one of those letters,

15:32.339 --> 15:34.829
then perhaps they found each other.

15:34.854 --> 15:37.636
Ergo, find Hattie, find Gabe.

15:37.661 --> 15:40.295
Of course, if they're not together...

15:40.320 --> 15:43.105
- Hattie might still have information...
<i>- Got something!</i>

15:43.225 --> 15:45.788
New Orleans yellow pages 2004 to 2005,

15:45.813 --> 15:48.525
there's a club called
Hattie's Backstreet Blues,

15:48.550 --> 15:51.253
45 St. James street.

15:51.278 --> 15:53.511
"Try our famous oysters.

15:53.547 --> 15:55.347
"Open mic night every Tuesday."

15:56.349 --> 15:58.871
- Nothing's coming up.
- All right, give me a second.

16:00.247 --> 16:02.113
Um...

16:02.672 --> 16:05.931
Yellow pages 2006, 2007...

16:07.329 --> 16:09.196
Um... yeah,

16:09.221 --> 16:11.956
there's nothing listed at
all after hurricane Katrina.

16:14.253 --> 16:16.104
Because it's gone.

16:21.696 --> 16:22.941
It's not hopeless.

16:22.976 --> 16:24.825
If Hattie's place was destroyed,

16:24.850 --> 16:27.145
then she may have applied
for a federal relief loan.

16:27.265 --> 16:28.481
And if that's the case,

16:28.506 --> 16:30.773
then I can hack into any
number of government records...

16:30.798 --> 16:33.421
[Clears throat] Ms. Mclnerney,
I am quite confident

16:33.446 --> 16:35.813
that you and your
computer could infiltrate

16:35.838 --> 16:37.824
the deepest galaxies of cyberspace,

16:37.849 --> 16:39.192
but please,

16:39.312 --> 16:42.192
don't say anything we might
have to repeat in court.

16:42.217 --> 16:43.255
Fair enough,

16:43.280 --> 16:45.413
but we still have to find
her last name somehow.

16:45.438 --> 16:46.570
Any ideas?

16:46.595 --> 16:48.301
I once got my name in the newspaper,

16:48.326 --> 16:49.358
sort of.

16:49.383 --> 16:50.911
You did? I didn't know that.

16:50.936 --> 16:53.720
I don't talk about it much.
And the charges were dropped.

16:53.840 --> 16:55.336
You were arrested?

16:55.361 --> 16:57.343
It was just a
misunderstanding at the zoo.

16:57.368 --> 16:59.377
I was actually trying
to return the penguin.

16:59.402 --> 17:01.856
Wait, I remember that
story. That was you?

17:01.976 --> 17:05.134
Yeah, "man cleared in
runaway penguin escapade."

17:05.159 --> 17:06.490
I was the unidentified man.

17:06.515 --> 17:08.782
Norman, you're a genius.

17:08.808 --> 17:11.238
Here we go, from the New
Orleans Times Picayune,

17:11.358 --> 17:13.128
August 10th, 2002.

17:13.154 --> 17:14.854
"... also petitioning the city council

17:14.878 --> 17:16.463
"in support of the
proposed traffic light

17:16.488 --> 17:17.988
"was local business owner

17:18.012 --> 17:19.468
"Amelia Grey Hatfield,

17:19.492 --> 17:21.970
"proprietor of Hattie's
Backstreet Blues Club."

17:21.994 --> 17:23.635
Of course, Hatfield!

17:23.660 --> 17:25.231
Hattie is her nickname!

17:25.256 --> 17:27.676
- Ooh, I wish I had a nickname.
- I'll think of one.

17:27.797 --> 17:29.834
Excellent work, Ms. Mclnerney.

17:30.010 --> 17:32.740
Well, now the fun starts. I've
got a search program here

17:32.860 --> 17:34.802
that I can adapt to
filter for old records,

17:34.827 --> 17:37.354
or relief applications,
or evacuee lists,

17:37.379 --> 17:38.786
anything Katrina-related

17:38.811 --> 17:40.110
that might help us see

17:40.135 --> 17:41.989
where Hattie may have ended up.

17:42.592 --> 17:43.891
Start.

17:44.079 --> 17:46.079
- _
- Now we just have to wait.

17:51.319 --> 17:52.442
No...

17:52.562 --> 17:55.328
No, no, no, no...

17:56.550 --> 17:58.050
Eleanor's kombucha recipe.

17:58.170 --> 18:00.037
I think I left it in the box

18:00.062 --> 18:02.741
of old reader's digests
that I had Norman throw out.

18:02.766 --> 18:04.172
I'm sorry. What did I do?

18:04.197 --> 18:06.044
- I'm sorry.
- No, it's not your fault.

18:06.243 --> 18:08.544
Now I'll never make one as good as hers.

18:08.579 --> 18:10.312
I'm sorry, Ms. Mclnerney.

18:10.348 --> 18:13.091
I know how much that "kumbacha" recipe

18:13.211 --> 18:15.150
- meant to you.
- "Kombucha."

18:15.186 --> 18:16.318
"Kum-bah-cha."

18:16.354 --> 18:18.636
- "Kom-bu-cha."
- "Kum-bah-cha."

18:18.756 --> 18:20.058
Forget it.

18:20.178 --> 18:21.957
I need chocolate.

18:23.827 --> 18:26.572
Serious... Serious chocolate.

18:29.266 --> 18:31.033
It feels so decadent
to be having dessert

18:31.068 --> 18:32.568
in the middle of the afternoon.

18:32.609 --> 18:34.826
Well, Reets, somewhere in
the world, it's dinnertime.

18:34.946 --> 18:37.288
- "Reets?"
- Yeah, I'm working on your nickname.

18:37.313 --> 18:39.174
Oh. Let's keep working on it.

18:39.210 --> 18:41.210
- [Chuckles awkwardly]
- Uh... Reetster?

18:41.245 --> 18:43.212
Uh... Reety-reety?

18:43.247 --> 18:44.546
Uh... Reets-meets?

18:44.582 --> 18:46.419
- [Groaning] No...
- That's bad.

18:46.884 --> 18:48.250
It's running every name

18:48.285 --> 18:49.918
registered with the city of New Orleans

18:49.954 --> 18:52.198
during the weeks after Katrina,
and if that doesn't work,

18:52.318 --> 18:54.990
I'll move on to state
and federal records.

18:55.026 --> 18:56.227
Remarkable.

18:58.796 --> 19:00.274
I think...

19:00.865 --> 19:04.033
We should read on a bit while we wait.

19:04.377 --> 19:05.645
Wow.

19:05.976 --> 19:08.185
Oliver O'Toole breaking protocol.

19:08.305 --> 19:09.838
What is that all about?

19:09.874 --> 19:11.381
I'm, um...

19:12.243 --> 19:14.209
Not sure. [Chuckles]

19:14.245 --> 19:15.511
Ovilear!

19:15.536 --> 19:16.635
Ramon!

19:16.660 --> 19:18.526
Ramon, what are you doing here?

19:18.551 --> 19:21.728
- Yeah, what are you doing here?
- Well, I have great news!

19:21.848 --> 19:24.601
I am the new owner
of the Mailbox Grille.

19:24.721 --> 19:26.637
- [Laughing in delight]
- Are you kidding me?

19:26.757 --> 19:28.290
Why? Why?

19:28.325 --> 19:29.892
It is a marvelous venue!

19:29.927 --> 19:32.017
And I have great plans for it.

19:32.137 --> 19:33.303
I see...

19:33.328 --> 19:34.730
A Sunday brunch.

19:34.850 --> 19:36.065
Perhaps...

19:36.100 --> 19:37.866
A mailbox Martini menu,

19:37.902 --> 19:40.755
and, of course, we must
improve on the jukebox, eh?

19:40.875 --> 19:42.971
Oh, that's right, you
know a lot about music.

19:43.007 --> 19:44.206
Oliver,

19:44.241 --> 19:46.141
can Ramon listen to the rest of letter?

19:46.177 --> 19:48.529
He might be able to hear
something that we don't.

19:48.649 --> 19:50.245
- Oh, I don't...
- Ah!

19:54.752 --> 19:57.809
"I know you could've gotten
somebody else to fix the bar,

19:57.929 --> 20:00.117
"but maybe you could
tell I needed the work,

20:00.458 --> 20:02.424
"and the company... "

20:03.201 --> 20:04.947
[♪♪♪]

20:05.067 --> 20:06.604
Darn this thing.

20:06.629 --> 20:08.696
I can come back and fix that tomorrow.

20:08.966 --> 20:10.667
That'd be fine by me.

20:11.082 --> 20:12.750
But it needs a special hinge,

20:12.870 --> 20:14.670
and the good ones are hard to find.

20:14.705 --> 20:16.271
I know.

20:16.307 --> 20:19.074
[♪♪♪]

20:22.179 --> 20:24.780
♪ People come ♪

20:24.815 --> 20:27.064
♪ and people go ♪

20:28.652 --> 20:31.730
♪ they take and they give ♪

20:32.656 --> 20:35.548
♪ and they build you up ♪

20:35.668 --> 20:38.338
♪ just to let you down ♪

20:39.697 --> 20:42.843
♪ that's just the way it is... ♪

20:43.464 --> 20:47.132
♪ 'Cause all I need is one friend ♪

20:47.872 --> 20:50.014
♪ to get me through the day ♪

20:50.841 --> 20:55.385
♪ one friend who never goes away ♪

20:55.464 --> 20:58.514
♪ only one friend♪

20:58.745 --> 21:01.352
♪ to understand ♪

21:01.892 --> 21:05.967
♪ and never let me down... ♪

21:07.525 --> 21:10.526
[♪♪♪]

21:12.030 --> 21:14.347
[Oliver reads]: <i>"... And I have
a confession to make. </i>

21:14.467 --> 21:16.798
"I could have fixed
that gate in one try.

21:16.834 --> 21:19.401
"But the truth is, that
was the first time I'd sung,

21:19.436 --> 21:21.537
"or even smiled that
much in a long time,

21:21.572 --> 21:23.146
"and it felt so good,

21:23.266 --> 21:25.340
"I just didn't want to leave.

21:25.376 --> 21:27.876
<i>"So, I pretended</i>

21:27.912 --> 21:29.978
<i>"I couldn't find the
right parts to the hinge.</i>

21:30.014 --> 21:33.815
<i>"But nothing ever gets by you, Hattie."</i>

21:33.851 --> 21:36.251
<i>♪ It's you I appreciate ♪</i>

21:36.287 --> 21:38.887
<i>♪ send me on my way... ♪</i>

21:38.923 --> 21:42.333
♪ kissed me on the lips
and said "have a nice day" ♪

21:42.453 --> 21:45.136
♪ she had me right where she wanted me ♪

21:45.652 --> 21:48.853
♪ you know what I was in a trance ♪

21:49.231 --> 21:50.556
♪ whew ♪

21:51.428 --> 21:54.229
♪ she said, "ain't nothin'
wrong with Texas ♪"

21:54.254 --> 21:57.856
♪ "but I'd really love
to go to France..." ♪

21:58.542 --> 22:00.286
[♪♪♪]

22:00.406 --> 22:01.845
Very scary.

22:09.364 --> 22:11.598
♪ It's no secret I don't care ♪

22:11.837 --> 22:14.120
♪ gonna shout it out everywhere ♪

22:14.158 --> 22:17.601
♪ love my baby hot,
cold, fast, or slow ♪

22:19.136 --> 22:20.596
- ♪ love my... ♪
- Uh-oh.

22:20.631 --> 22:22.596
[Laughter]

22:24.940 --> 22:27.541
♪ In the evening in my bed ♪

22:27.701 --> 22:29.946
♪ I hear voices in my head ♪

22:30.767 --> 22:32.400
There you go.

22:32.842 --> 22:34.675
Good as new.

22:36.447 --> 22:37.946
Better.

22:40.140 --> 22:42.024
[Knock on door]

22:42.049 --> 22:43.792
We're closed!

22:46.624 --> 22:48.719
Hurricane's coming.

22:48.839 --> 22:50.469
It's gonna be a big one.

22:52.863 --> 22:54.529
I lived through Camille.

22:55.799 --> 22:57.645
I can get through this one.

22:58.335 --> 23:00.101
I'm sure you can.

23:00.486 --> 23:01.585
But...

23:02.106 --> 23:05.472
I was thinking maybe you
might like a little company.

23:08.479 --> 23:09.781
Well...

23:10.014 --> 23:11.824
I could close up early,

23:12.228 --> 23:13.315
and...

23:17.454 --> 23:19.498
We could weather it out together.

23:20.057 --> 23:21.540
I have lots of food...

23:22.125 --> 23:24.592
And lots of ginger ale.

23:25.996 --> 23:27.896
Well, I'll see you tomorrow.

23:35.472 --> 23:37.806
[Oliver reads]: <i>"The next
day they made us evacuate,</i>

23:37.841 --> 23:39.651
<i>"and then the levees broke,</i>

23:39.676 --> 23:43.101
<i>"and Hattie, I tried everything I could</i>

23:43.126 --> 23:44.692
<i>"to get back to you,</i>

23:44.717 --> 23:46.750
<i>"but I couldn't even get close.</i>

23:46.775 --> 23:49.944
<i>"I lost my home, I lost my toolbox,</i>

23:50.854 --> 23:53.666
<i>"I lost everything but my guitar.</i>

23:54.358 --> 23:56.725
<i>"But my only regret is waiting too long</i>

23:56.760 --> 23:58.509
<i>"to tell you how I feel.</i>

23:58.817 --> 24:01.241
<i>"I kept thinking I had tomorrow... </i>

24:01.600 --> 24:04.155
"Somebody on this bus
thinks it's going to Denver,

24:04.180 --> 24:05.577
"and if that's true,

24:05.697 --> 24:07.035
"then you'll know how to find me

24:07.071 --> 24:08.314
"if you want to,

24:08.575 --> 24:11.205
"'cause I'm gonna do what
you taught me to do."

24:11.442 --> 24:13.809
What did she teach him to do?

24:13.844 --> 24:16.070
Yeah! What did she teach
him to do? I don't think

24:16.190 --> 24:18.202
- that's mentioned anywhere.
- Neither do I.

24:19.292 --> 24:21.205
"I'm going to do what
you taught me to do.

24:21.230 --> 24:23.677
"I'm gonna find my higher ground,

24:23.961 --> 24:26.828
"and I'll be there every Sunday morning,

24:26.853 --> 24:28.819
"waiting for the rest of my life.

24:28.844 --> 24:31.581
"And I promise, if there's
another bus to Denver,

24:31.701 --> 24:33.268
"and you get on it and find me,

24:33.293 --> 24:35.693
"I'll never lose you again.

24:36.008 --> 24:38.176
"Always, Gabe."

24:38.803 --> 24:40.047
You were right.

24:40.312 --> 24:41.912
He was in love.

24:42.172 --> 24:44.125
No matter how many letters he sent,

24:44.150 --> 24:47.618
they all went to a place
that doesn't exist anymore.

24:47.643 --> 24:49.176
12 years,

24:49.201 --> 24:51.467
and so many hearts are still broken.

24:53.930 --> 24:56.631
Well, we're trying to
mend at least one of them.

24:56.656 --> 24:57.922
I found her.

24:57.947 --> 24:59.614
Great!

24:59.763 --> 25:02.497
Amelia Grey Hatfield is listed as...

25:02.743 --> 25:04.376
Missing and

25:04.670 --> 25:06.369
presumed dead.

25:16.122 --> 25:17.237
<i>Poor Gabe.</i>

25:17.357 --> 25:18.523
<i>Poor Hattie.</i>

25:18.558 --> 25:20.191
She was waiting for him,

25:20.227 --> 25:21.648
but he never came.

25:21.673 --> 25:24.084
And he's out there waiting for her,

25:24.204 --> 25:26.431
but she's never going to come.

25:26.551 --> 25:28.214
Perhaps he's given up by now.

25:28.334 --> 25:29.701
Never.

25:29.736 --> 25:32.203
True love never gives up.

25:32.239 --> 25:34.303
You must find this Gabriel.

25:34.908 --> 25:36.408
This is...

25:36.443 --> 25:38.677
This is very upsetting.

25:38.712 --> 25:41.975
At times like this,
all I can do is pray,

25:42.095 --> 25:45.032
and, of course, eat my
mother's famous pozole.

25:45.152 --> 25:47.085
"Priority mail pozole"... ?

25:48.588 --> 25:49.750
Excuse me.

25:51.158 --> 25:53.692
Leave it to Ramon to
take lemons and make...

25:53.727 --> 25:55.239
Soup.

25:55.359 --> 25:57.195
Well, I hate to say it,

25:57.230 --> 25:59.931
I mean, I really hate to say it, but...

26:00.492 --> 26:02.467
Ramon's got a point.

26:02.502 --> 26:05.270
You don't just stop loving somebody,

26:05.305 --> 26:08.194
especially if you've been
lonely your whole life,

26:08.234 --> 26:10.303
and then, one day, you walk in,

26:10.423 --> 26:12.410
and you meet somebody
who makes you laugh,

26:12.822 --> 26:15.187
and sees all the good things about you,

26:15.307 --> 26:17.408
- makes you feel special...
- Hey...

26:17.528 --> 26:20.158
We thought Hattie would lead us to Gabe.

26:20.278 --> 26:22.216
Now we just have to find another way.

26:22.336 --> 26:24.322
We are the postables.

26:24.357 --> 26:27.189
We have wide powers of postal discretion

26:27.309 --> 26:28.893
that we haven't even used yet,

26:28.929 --> 26:30.128
right, Norman?

26:30.163 --> 26:32.330
Then that's what we'll do.

26:32.365 --> 26:34.933
And we'll start first
thing Monday morning.

26:35.762 --> 26:36.935
Monday.

26:54.020 --> 26:55.420
[Rings doorbell]

27:05.490 --> 27:06.613
Hi.

27:06.733 --> 27:08.600
Good evening, Ms... Uh, Shane.

27:08.720 --> 27:09.868
[Chuckles]

27:09.903 --> 27:11.608
Good evening, Oliver.

27:11.728 --> 27:13.277
You look beautiful.

27:13.397 --> 27:14.572
Thank you.

27:15.743 --> 27:17.442
Our conversation yesterday

27:17.477 --> 27:19.790
put me in mind of a small jazz club

27:19.910 --> 27:21.225
on Pearl Street.

27:21.542 --> 27:24.149
I thought we might
start there for drinks,

27:24.184 --> 27:27.352
then we have a table
at Montaldo's at 7:00.

27:27.387 --> 27:29.304
Well, that sounds just...

27:30.278 --> 27:32.205
- That's funny.
- What?

27:32.325 --> 27:33.594
Your tie.

27:33.714 --> 27:35.493
You tied it in a Windsor.

27:35.834 --> 27:39.130
But you only wear a
Windsor on Wednesdays.

27:39.166 --> 27:40.698
Huh...

27:43.036 --> 27:44.750
It's a beautiful night.

27:44.870 --> 27:47.172
- Would you like to walk?
- I'd love to.

27:47.207 --> 27:49.140
[Thunder rumbles]

27:52.090 --> 27:54.297
Have you ever noticed
every time we try and

27:54.417 --> 27:56.527
have a nice evening, something happens?

27:56.647 --> 27:58.650
Maybe God's trying to tell us something.

27:58.770 --> 28:00.819
- And that would be...
<i>- Table for two?</i>

28:00.854 --> 28:02.200
Oh, hi.

28:05.209 --> 28:07.091
- [Laughing together]
- ... yes! You don't agree?

28:07.127 --> 28:09.160
No, it's apples and oranges.

28:09.196 --> 28:12.020
Jazz is not about the
notes that you hear,

28:12.140 --> 28:14.332
it's about the notes
that you don't hear,

28:14.367 --> 28:16.664
and with the blues, it's
not about what you hear,

28:16.784 --> 28:19.097
it's what you feel. It's

28:19.217 --> 28:21.351
rhythm and truth.

28:21.775 --> 28:24.909
It's pain, set to music.

28:24.945 --> 28:26.578
That's very profound

28:26.613 --> 28:27.946
coming from a woman

28:27.981 --> 28:30.931
who drinks "Kambacha" in the
afternoon and Martinis at night.

28:31.051 --> 28:33.781
[Laughs] Give me your pen.

28:37.791 --> 28:40.006
- Ooh.
- It was my grandfather's.

28:40.126 --> 28:41.893
It's perfect.

28:41.928 --> 28:44.963
Now, watch and learn.

28:44.998 --> 28:46.139
[Chuckles]

28:46.259 --> 28:48.200
You're gonna have to open your mind

28:48.320 --> 28:50.161
and use your imagination.

28:50.281 --> 28:52.070
I can do that.

28:52.105 --> 28:54.939
When I close my eyes,
and I listen to jazz,

28:54.975 --> 28:56.884
this is what I see...

28:58.144 --> 29:00.712
Surprise, and light,

29:00.747 --> 29:02.830
crazy possibility.

29:06.453 --> 29:07.819
But when I close my eyes,

29:07.854 --> 29:10.107
and I listen to the blues, I don't...

29:11.679 --> 29:13.807
I don't see it...

29:13.927 --> 29:16.561
I just feel it.

29:18.031 --> 29:20.005
And sometimes, it's full,

29:20.125 --> 29:22.433
sometimes, it's empty,

29:22.469 --> 29:25.103
sometimes, it's broken.

29:25.582 --> 29:27.272
But it's always...

29:27.307 --> 29:29.337
It just always feels so...

29:29.457 --> 29:31.676
Painfully but exquisitely true.

29:31.711 --> 29:33.185
I imagine.

29:35.015 --> 29:36.487
Yes.

29:37.328 --> 29:38.718
Very good.

29:38.838 --> 29:41.964
Did I pass the course?

29:42.084 --> 29:43.302
Mm-hmm.

29:44.824 --> 29:47.260
May I have my pen back now?

29:47.380 --> 29:48.673
No.

29:48.793 --> 29:50.523
There may be a test later.

29:53.633 --> 29:56.860
I'm afraid we missed our reservation.

29:57.506 --> 29:59.225
I have no doubt we'll make it back

29:59.345 --> 30:01.755
to Montaldo's someday, at some point.

30:01.875 --> 30:03.508
[Laughing]

30:09.883 --> 30:12.037
You know the porch swing you gave me?

30:12.157 --> 30:14.231
- Of course.
- Well, remember it

30:14.351 --> 30:15.853
was a little off-balance?

30:15.889 --> 30:18.389
I thought I'd fixed
that. Is it still off?

30:18.425 --> 30:19.557
No.

30:19.677 --> 30:21.725
It just has a little...

30:21.845 --> 30:23.528
Squeak now.

30:24.342 --> 30:27.802
Maybe I should take a look at it.

30:27.922 --> 30:30.165
That would be nice.

30:38.444 --> 30:41.561
Earlier on, you said
something about, um...

30:41.681 --> 30:43.047
About?

30:43.082 --> 30:44.808
Well, you said something about God.

30:44.928 --> 30:47.800
Oh. Well, it's like you said,

30:47.920 --> 30:50.354
just that every time we try to go out,

30:50.389 --> 30:52.154
something seems to happen.

30:52.274 --> 30:53.423
Maybe...

30:53.543 --> 30:56.393
God's trying to tell us something.

30:56.429 --> 30:58.996
Hmm, interesting, and, um,

30:59.031 --> 31:01.599
what do you think he might be saying?

31:01.634 --> 31:05.202
Maybe he's saying that this is crazy,

31:05.238 --> 31:06.652
- you and...
- Oh, my Goodness!

31:06.772 --> 31:08.405
Oh, I'm okay. I'm okay.

31:08.441 --> 31:09.854
- Are you all right?
- Yes.

31:09.974 --> 31:12.009
Shall we call a cab?

31:12.044 --> 31:14.278
We could...

31:14.313 --> 31:17.548
But then I'd have to let go.

31:21.254 --> 31:23.153
<i>[♪♪♪]</i>

31:26.312 --> 31:29.593
[Car horn honks]

31:29.629 --> 31:31.595
Shall we walk?

31:33.432 --> 31:36.333
<i>[♪♪♪]</i>

32:05.358 --> 32:07.405
What do you thinking about?

32:08.526 --> 32:10.659
I was just thinking

32:10.694 --> 32:13.777
about how I almost quit the DLO.

32:13.897 --> 32:15.731
You did quit, more than twice.

32:15.766 --> 32:17.299
[Laughs]

32:17.334 --> 32:19.501
But I didn't, because I...

32:19.537 --> 32:21.421
Because...?

32:24.308 --> 32:26.074
[Porch swing squeaks]

32:27.278 --> 32:28.580
Steve?

32:30.481 --> 32:32.454
<i>You got a squeak in this thing.</i>

32:34.464 --> 32:36.518
- What are you doing here?
- Oliver.

32:36.554 --> 32:38.487
Mr. Marek.

32:38.522 --> 32:40.939
Sorry to drop in like
this, but could we...

32:41.059 --> 32:42.873
Could we speak privately?

32:42.993 --> 32:44.426
No.

32:44.462 --> 32:48.197
This isn't a personal visit, Shane.

32:48.232 --> 32:50.265
There's a crisis in D.C.,
and I need you there now.

32:50.301 --> 32:51.774
Well, tonight.

32:51.894 --> 32:54.036
What? Are you crazy?

32:54.071 --> 32:56.138
It's a crisis situation,

32:56.173 --> 32:57.639
I need the best hackers in the business,

32:57.675 --> 32:59.475
and I need somebody who knows the USPS.

32:59.510 --> 33:01.043
Has our security been breached?

33:01.078 --> 33:03.248
- I can...
- Neither confirm nor deny,

33:03.368 --> 33:04.513
yes, I remember.

33:04.548 --> 33:06.515
Look, you gotta trust me on this.

33:07.256 --> 33:09.485
You need to go inside, pack a bag,

33:09.520 --> 33:11.770
grab your passport. We've
got a plane waiting for us

33:11.890 --> 33:13.121
at Buckley air field.

33:13.157 --> 33:15.547
How long will this... ?

33:15.667 --> 33:18.262
I don't know, maybe a few weeks?

33:23.856 --> 33:27.145
You are the best at what
you do, Ms. McInerney.

33:28.272 --> 33:29.872
[Sighs]

33:29.907 --> 33:31.874
Rita has a key.

33:31.909 --> 33:33.614
And the rose bush, it needs

33:33.734 --> 33:35.577
- to be trimmed back, or else...
- I will handle things.

33:35.697 --> 33:38.787
I will handle things. Just call
us with your address and

33:38.907 --> 33:40.931
- I'll forward your mail until you...
- Oliver...

33:41.051 --> 33:42.729
We're gonna have to go
radio silence on this.

33:42.849 --> 33:45.554
That means no calls, no texts,
no emails, no regular mail...

33:45.589 --> 33:47.259
- Yes, but surely...
- Once they're broken up

33:47.379 --> 33:49.064
into their teams, they're
gonna be incommunicado

33:49.184 --> 33:51.426
for the duration. Now,
we really gotta roll.

33:55.184 --> 33:56.632
[Clears throat]

34:01.105 --> 34:02.738
I'll be back.

34:02.773 --> 34:04.706
Of course.

34:05.976 --> 34:07.709
I...

34:07.745 --> 34:09.493
I really enjoyed our walk.

34:12.315 --> 34:14.248
So did I.

34:16.487 --> 34:18.520
Promise me that you'll find Gabe.

34:18.556 --> 34:21.723
But tell him not to
be too hard on himself.

34:21.759 --> 34:24.626
He didn't have to say it.

34:24.661 --> 34:27.601
She knew that he loved her.

34:28.232 --> 34:30.032
She knew.

34:32.303 --> 34:34.603
I will tell him.

34:52.322 --> 34:53.873
Her passport?

34:54.824 --> 34:57.426
Will she be safe?

34:59.296 --> 35:02.798
I'd die before I let
anything happen to her.

35:15.813 --> 35:18.880
[Porch swing squeaking]

35:27.191 --> 35:30.241
I don't know what's worse.
Having your date hijacked

35:30.361 --> 35:32.995
by an incredibly handsome man
from the Clandestine Services,

35:33.030 --> 35:35.130
or having him be her ex boyfriend.

35:35.165 --> 35:38.014
Oh, the waiting for her
to come back, Norman,

35:38.134 --> 35:39.835
that's got to be the worst.

35:39.870 --> 35:41.950
And without tech support, how
are we supposed to find Gabe?

35:42.070 --> 35:44.255
- We don't have anything left to go on.
- Well, we still have us.

35:44.375 --> 35:45.707
Hmm.

35:45.743 --> 35:48.210
We'll think of something then, Ree-ree.

35:48.245 --> 35:50.045
"Ree-ree?"

35:50.080 --> 35:52.147
[Chuckles doubtfully] Uh-uh.

35:52.182 --> 35:53.914
<i>Well, that's a new one.</i>

35:54.034 --> 35:57.452
"Homeland Security stole my girl."

35:57.488 --> 36:00.455
Or did you... Let her go?

36:00.491 --> 36:03.392
It was her decision.

36:03.427 --> 36:05.460
Question,

36:05.496 --> 36:07.129
does she know how you feel?

36:07.164 --> 36:09.775
Shoot, do you know how you feel?

36:11.235 --> 36:13.162
When we were lost

36:13.282 --> 36:15.470
up on that mountain last month,

36:15.506 --> 36:19.007
and I almost lost, uh, everything...

36:20.411 --> 36:22.678
After that, I told her how I felt.

36:22.713 --> 36:24.579
Actually, I told her how I felt

36:24.615 --> 36:26.682
about being ready to feel something

36:26.717 --> 36:28.479
about how I feel.

36:29.019 --> 36:31.520
And she followed that?

36:31.555 --> 36:33.768
Well, I was as clear
as I know how to be.

36:33.888 --> 36:35.057
Hmm.

36:35.727 --> 36:37.225
And I kissed her.

36:39.196 --> 36:40.918
It was brief, but, uh...

36:42.199 --> 36:43.586
Very, uh...

36:44.286 --> 36:47.135
If you get another
chance to kiss her, son...

36:49.073 --> 36:51.173
Take your time.

36:56.280 --> 36:58.080
<i>[♪♪♪]</i>

37:06.990 --> 37:09.884
<i>♪ None of business ♪</i>

37:10.004 --> 37:13.777
- _
<i>- ♪ gettin' all of my concern ♪</i>

37:13.897 --> 37:16.965
<i>♪ tried to put out the fire ♪</i>

37:17.000 --> 37:19.568
<i>♪ but the flame's still burning ♪</i>

37:19.603 --> 37:23.238
<i>♪ oh, and as she pleases
she comes and goes ♪</i>

37:23.273 --> 37:26.099
<i>♪ she's got the wind in her hair ♪</i>

37:26.219 --> 37:29.125
<i>♪ oh, she never ceases to hurt me so ♪</i>

37:29.245 --> 37:32.403
<i>♪ does she really care? ♪</i>

37:33.617 --> 37:36.985
<i>♪ Is she ever comin' home? ♪</i>

37:37.020 --> 37:41.409
<i>♪ Is she ever gonna phone? ♪</i>

37:42.459 --> 37:44.826
<i>♪ Another night alone ♪</i>

37:44.862 --> 37:49.182
<i>♪ has anybody seen my girl? ♪</i>

37:52.337 --> 37:55.989
<i>♪ Has anybody seen my woman? ♪</i>

37:57.941 --> 38:01.069
<i>♪ California ♪</i>

38:01.690 --> 38:03.894
<i>♪ to Tennessee ♪</i>

38:04.014 --> 38:07.600
<i>♪ send my baby ♪</i>

38:07.720 --> 38:10.067
<i>♪ home to me ♪</i>

38:10.187 --> 38:12.254
<i>♪ home to me... ♪</i>

38:13.524 --> 38:15.457
<i>[♪♪♪]</i>

38:15.492 --> 38:17.359
<i>♪ Where am I going? ♪</i>

38:17.394 --> 38:20.063
<i>♪ Oh, what am I gonna do? ♪</i>

38:21.832 --> 38:25.834
<i>♪ I know I'm not crazy no,
no, I'm just hooked you ♪</i>

38:25.869 --> 38:30.705
<i>♪ so go on and use me endlessly ♪</i>

38:30.741 --> 38:33.975
<i>♪ but could you let me know ♪</i>

38:34.011 --> 38:37.379
<i>♪ when you need me hold me close ♪</i>

38:37.414 --> 38:40.510
<i>♪ and baby, don't let go... ♪</i>

38:40.818 --> 38:44.080
<i>[♪♪♪]</i>

38:44.822 --> 38:46.932
Norman, come here, come here!

38:47.052 --> 38:48.319
What?

38:49.760 --> 38:51.359
Look...

38:51.395 --> 38:53.562
There's little sprouts.

38:53.597 --> 38:55.520
Aw, they grow up so fast.

38:55.640 --> 38:57.132
<i>Oh, dear.</i>

39:03.273 --> 39:04.673
Oliver?

39:05.776 --> 39:07.808
- How's it going?
- Any luck?

39:08.295 --> 39:09.716
I'm sorry to say,

39:09.836 --> 39:13.682
but without Ms. McInerney's
advance search protocols,

39:13.717 --> 39:15.150
it's taken us four weeks

39:15.185 --> 39:17.501
what she might have
accomplished in a day.

39:17.621 --> 39:19.686
Yeah, I'm still filling
out request forms

39:19.806 --> 39:21.990
for evacuation rolls from 2005.

39:22.110 --> 39:23.509
Maybe...

39:24.155 --> 39:27.662
we should try all
the churches in Denver?

39:27.698 --> 39:30.398
Remember he said something
about "every Sunday morning"?

39:30.434 --> 39:33.335
That's 1057 churches, though.

39:33.370 --> 39:36.383
No, I know it's a lot to ask,
but I made a promise to...

39:39.088 --> 39:42.010
Uh... myself. I-I can't give up on this.

39:43.413 --> 39:47.074
<i>♪ ... has anybody seen my woman ♪</i>

39:50.587 --> 39:52.738
<i>♪ from California ♪</i>

39:53.757 --> 39:56.625
<i>♪ to Tennessee ♪</i>

39:56.660 --> 39:58.946
♪ send my baby ♪

39:59.591 --> 40:02.012
<i>♪ home to me ♪</i>

40:02.132 --> 40:04.032
<i>♪ home to me... ♪</i>

40:06.581 --> 40:09.382
Maria Gloria Patricia's pozole...

40:09.417 --> 40:11.668
Kate and I came here last
week and had it. It was great.

40:11.788 --> 40:13.640
- "Po... "
- "Po-tho-lay."

40:16.583 --> 40:19.674
Ooh... Ooh, it is spicy.

40:19.946 --> 40:21.894
It kind of gives you a...

40:22.014 --> 40:25.546
A lift, sort of a zip. [Laughing]

40:25.666 --> 40:28.051
Oliver could use some of that.

40:28.502 --> 40:30.936
He must be missing the beautiful Shane.

40:31.835 --> 40:33.928
Uh... if we're being honest,

40:34.048 --> 40:35.674
we're a little worried about him.

40:35.709 --> 40:38.425
- I am, too.
- Every night we leave the office,

40:38.545 --> 40:40.078
he's still there, sitting at his desk,

40:40.114 --> 40:41.690
- staring at her blender.
- [Sighs]

40:41.810 --> 40:44.016
The blender she never got to use.

40:44.817 --> 40:46.852
In my family, we have a tradition.

40:48.216 --> 40:49.739
If a friend is in trouble,

40:49.859 --> 40:52.925
we surround him with "the three Ps."

40:52.960 --> 40:54.359
"Passion... "

40:55.079 --> 40:56.328
"Pozole... "

40:57.531 --> 40:59.498
... and "poker."

41:00.159 --> 41:01.833
Poker?

41:01.869 --> 41:03.902
I love poker.

41:03.938 --> 41:05.616
<i>[♪♪♪]</i>

41:11.955 --> 41:13.600
... and if everybody folds,

41:13.720 --> 41:16.563
then the last man holding gets
the pot, and he doesn't even

41:16.683 --> 41:18.548
- have to show his cards.
- How is it that

41:18.668 --> 41:20.522
you know so much about poker?

41:20.642 --> 41:22.800
Well, I'm actually a Blackjack girl,

41:22.920 --> 41:24.856
but I'm pretty much
banned from every casino.

41:24.892 --> 41:26.458
You know, photographic memory,

41:26.493 --> 41:28.327
counting cards...  [Chuckles]

41:30.679 --> 41:32.264
You look like a general here.

41:32.299 --> 41:35.272
I was. Briefly. A small,
obsolete republic.

41:35.970 --> 41:37.752
You were a matador?

41:37.872 --> 41:39.504
Just to pay my way through school.

41:39.906 --> 41:41.940
Oh, Norman, can you grab the cheese

41:41.976 --> 41:44.476
wheel from the counter, please?

41:44.596 --> 41:47.713
You are a very fortunate man, Normando.

41:47.748 --> 41:49.892
How long have you two been together now?

41:50.012 --> 41:52.317
Oh, uh... just over a year, I guess.

41:52.353 --> 41:54.001
Ah. You know, in my country,

41:54.121 --> 41:55.946
you'd be married with twins by now.

41:56.066 --> 41:57.789
Everyone had twins there.

41:57.825 --> 41:59.396
Well, uh...

41:59.725 --> 42:01.075
We do have, um...

42:01.195 --> 42:02.358
A potato.

42:02.478 --> 42:04.062
Hmm.

42:08.927 --> 42:10.469
How is Ovilear doing?

42:10.504 --> 42:11.790
He seems a bit lost.

42:11.910 --> 42:14.422
Well, I think your money's safe tonight.

42:15.876 --> 42:17.642
But at least he's getting out a little.

42:20.965 --> 42:22.047
This is nice.

42:22.083 --> 42:23.215
Ah...

42:23.250 --> 42:26.819
The glory days of alternative
Latin garage punk grunge.

42:26.854 --> 42:30.189
I'm a blues man, myself.

42:32.093 --> 42:34.470
Whatever happened to that fellow

42:34.590 --> 42:36.579
in the letter? The man
from the hurricane?

42:36.699 --> 42:39.531
Oh, we tried everything,
but we never found him.

42:40.668 --> 42:41.907
Did you try music?

42:43.003 --> 42:44.355
How do you mean?

42:44.475 --> 42:47.005
Musicians are magnets
for other musicians,

42:47.041 --> 42:48.437
and as you know,

42:48.557 --> 42:51.043
I'm bringing live music
to the Mailbox Grille.

42:51.078 --> 42:53.748
Thursdays will be jazz night,

42:53.868 --> 42:56.181
Fridays are alternative Latin
garage punk grunge night,

42:56.217 --> 42:58.232
of course. But Saturdays...

42:58.352 --> 42:59.752
Are blues night!

42:59.787 --> 43:00.919
Now...

43:00.955 --> 43:03.178
If Gabriel is in this town,

43:03.298 --> 43:04.423
trust me,

43:04.458 --> 43:06.833
if we play it, he will come!

43:08.648 --> 43:11.230
[♪♪♪]

43:26.947 --> 43:28.447
[Song ends]

43:28.482 --> 43:31.984
[Applause]

43:36.430 --> 43:38.612
We've asked everyone if
they know a blues musician

43:38.732 --> 43:40.877
named Gabe, but nobody does.

43:40.997 --> 43:43.095
Yeah, Ramon was so sure
that the word would get out,

43:43.130 --> 43:45.382
and Gabe would show up
as long as the music was good.

43:45.502 --> 43:47.065
Well, this is only the first night,

43:47.101 --> 43:49.650
- and the band was excellent.
- Ovilear!

43:49.770 --> 43:52.306
My friends... I want you to meet

43:52.426 --> 43:54.039
big Joe Hopkins,

43:54.074 --> 43:55.307
Denver legend.

43:55.342 --> 43:57.240
He might be able to
help you in your search.

43:57.360 --> 43:59.611
- Oh.
- Oh, thank you. We love your music.

43:59.647 --> 44:01.625
This is a great spot.
We need a place like this.

44:01.745 --> 44:04.122
Ramon says you know every
blues player in town.

44:04.242 --> 44:05.651
We all kinda know each other.

44:05.686 --> 44:07.361
You wouldn't happen to know a gentleman

44:07.481 --> 44:09.254
by the name of Gabe from New Orleans?

44:09.290 --> 44:10.722
Gabe...

44:10.758 --> 44:12.090
What's his last name?

44:12.126 --> 44:14.644
Well, that's all we have, just Gabe.

44:14.764 --> 44:16.328
Doesn't ring a bell.

44:16.363 --> 44:18.397
But Ephraim Beals is from Louisiana.

44:18.432 --> 44:20.132
He plays over at the E-flat Lounge.

44:20.167 --> 44:22.267
Oh, yes, we've, um...

44:23.488 --> 44:25.218
Uh, I've been there.

44:28.203 --> 44:31.261
<i>Oh, I haven't been back to
New Orleans since Katrina.</i>

44:32.308 --> 44:35.080
Haven't got the money,
don't have the heart.

44:35.115 --> 44:36.281
Right.

44:36.317 --> 44:39.003
- I'm very sorry.
- So, who is it you're looking for?

44:39.123 --> 44:41.353
A man named Gabe, he
plays a guitar and sings.

44:41.388 --> 44:43.671
He was evacuated to
Denver, so we were hoping

44:43.791 --> 44:46.458
he still plays at a club somewhere here.

44:46.493 --> 44:48.126
Gabe...

44:48.162 --> 44:50.762
'Course, folks don't
use their real names.

44:50.798 --> 44:53.280
Like sunny Jack, bad boy Baker,

44:53.400 --> 44:55.434
and the 52-80 man...

44:55.469 --> 44:57.769
Folks just don't know
who they really are.

44:57.805 --> 44:59.705
Well, uh...

44:59.740 --> 45:02.107
Thank you very much for trying.

45:02.142 --> 45:04.543
It was a pleasure to meet you.

45:04.578 --> 45:06.044
I really like your music.

45:06.080 --> 45:07.279
It's very positive,

45:07.314 --> 45:09.755
considering how sad it is.
[Chuckles awkwardly]

45:09.875 --> 45:12.117
Well, here, take one of
my CDs home with you.

45:12.152 --> 45:13.605
Oh, thank you.

45:13.725 --> 45:15.988
Oh, "Walk a mile in my blues."

45:16.023 --> 45:18.474
That's very clever. "Walk a mile in... "

45:18.594 --> 45:19.861
"in my... "

45:21.323 --> 45:24.779
Wait, what was that you
said about the 52 man?

45:24.899 --> 45:26.798
The 52-80 man?

45:26.834 --> 45:29.034
Cat's a real mystery.

45:29.069 --> 45:30.636
Only plays his guitar

45:30.671 --> 45:32.304
on the steps of the State Capitol,

45:32.339 --> 45:33.932
one day a week.

45:34.052 --> 45:37.075
- Would that day be Sunday?
- Every Sunday.

45:37.195 --> 45:39.132
Folks call him "52-80" 'cause of the...

45:39.252 --> 45:41.346
Because the altitude of
the State Capitol is...

45:41.382 --> 45:43.093
exactly 5,280 feet,

45:43.213 --> 45:45.150
- which is...
- A mile!

45:45.430 --> 45:46.985
[Gasping in delight]

45:55.729 --> 45:57.062
Here...

46:01.135 --> 46:02.901
[Gasps] Found it!

46:02.937 --> 46:04.569
Return address is...

46:04.605 --> 46:07.906
"Gabe, a mile high."

46:07.942 --> 46:09.174
What time is it?

46:09.209 --> 46:12.444
Um... 1:15 A.M.

46:12.479 --> 46:14.579
It's Sunday morning.

46:22.756 --> 46:25.190
Oh, I hope he's there.

46:25.225 --> 46:26.391
Shh...

46:26.427 --> 46:28.026
Do you hear that?

46:28.062 --> 46:31.430
[Distant singing]

46:33.767 --> 46:35.059
♪ ... one way or another ♪

46:35.179 --> 46:37.469
♪ we're gonna find higher ground ♪

46:37.504 --> 46:41.606
♪ well, you might be deaf
or you might be blind ♪

46:41.642 --> 46:44.246
♪ but you put the message ♪

46:44.366 --> 46:46.560
♪ right in your mind ♪

46:46.680 --> 46:49.081
♪ might look like a plan ♪

46:49.116 --> 46:51.616
♪ or a coalition ♪

46:51.652 --> 46:54.241
♪ or it might be god trying to get ♪

46:54.361 --> 46:56.303
♪ your attention ♪

46:56.423 --> 46:59.041
♪ might be god trying to get ♪

46:59.161 --> 47:01.709
♪ your attention ♪

47:01.829 --> 47:02.894
♪ oh, yeah ♪

47:04.389 --> 47:06.365
Gabe?

47:10.436 --> 47:11.861
<i>Man, oh, man,</i>

47:11.949 --> 47:14.198
you all spent all this
time looking for me?

47:14.318 --> 47:15.584
Yup.

47:15.620 --> 47:16.807
That's our job.

47:17.624 --> 47:19.188
I'm afraid it was necessary

47:19.223 --> 47:21.377
to read the letter in
order to locate you.

47:21.497 --> 47:23.459
Then you know about Hattie.

47:23.494 --> 47:24.960
Not much.

47:24.996 --> 47:27.263
We were able to ascertain

47:27.298 --> 47:29.131
that the Backstreet Blues Club is...

47:29.167 --> 47:30.399
Gone.

47:32.236 --> 47:34.691
I tried to call a few times,

47:34.811 --> 47:36.385
but I finally figured it

47:36.505 --> 47:38.103
got wiped out.

47:39.642 --> 47:41.711
But I did write a few more letters,

47:41.746 --> 47:44.447
hoping that maybe Hattie
had a forwarding address

47:44.482 --> 47:46.390
or something.

47:47.285 --> 47:48.888
I've still got hope.

47:50.288 --> 47:52.397
I figured you gotta have hope.

47:53.347 --> 47:56.125
Wait, so you've been
waiting all this time

47:56.160 --> 47:57.728
for Hattie to find you?

47:57.848 --> 48:00.463
12 years is a long time.

48:02.235 --> 48:05.256
There was something really
powerful about that lady.

48:05.376 --> 48:07.169
You know, when she put
her mind to something,

48:07.205 --> 48:08.970
nothing could stop her,

48:10.615 --> 48:12.541
and that's what I'm counting on.

48:13.511 --> 48:14.777
What do you mean?

48:16.781 --> 48:19.115
One night we stayed up all night long,

48:19.150 --> 48:21.733
and we talked, and we talked,
we talked about everything.

48:21.853 --> 48:24.969
She got me talking more that night
than I've talked my whole life

48:25.089 --> 48:27.456
- put together.
- [Chuckling]

48:27.492 --> 48:30.393
I told her how I had a good life,

48:30.428 --> 48:32.921
and I had a good wife,

48:33.041 --> 48:34.931
and a baby girl,

48:34.966 --> 48:38.467
and how a grease fire started
in our apartment building

48:38.503 --> 48:39.902
and took it all away,

48:39.938 --> 48:42.539
while I was singing and playing
<i>down in the quarter... </i>

48:43.087 --> 48:45.062
They were killed in a fire

48:45.182 --> 48:46.642
- in our apartment.
- I'm so sorry.

48:46.678 --> 48:48.461
I even heard the sirens on their way

48:48.581 --> 48:50.138
faintly in the distance.

48:50.258 --> 48:51.781
You know, I didn't put it together.

48:51.816 --> 48:54.012
Of course, you don't
think it's your house.

48:54.132 --> 48:55.521
But it was,

48:55.862 --> 48:57.435
and I just lost it.

48:57.555 --> 49:00.990
I haven't played another note since.

49:01.025 --> 49:03.192
I haven't played at all...

49:03.227 --> 49:04.979
Till I came in here.

49:05.099 --> 49:07.763
You're gonna see them
again someday, baby,

49:07.799 --> 49:09.498
you know that.

49:09.534 --> 49:10.848
But for now,

49:10.968 --> 49:13.202
you gotta hand all
that over to the Lord,

49:13.237 --> 49:15.136
and you gotta keep singing.

49:15.707 --> 49:17.926
That's what you were born to do.

49:19.811 --> 49:22.311
What you need is vision.

49:22.347 --> 49:26.682
And it is hard to get vision
down here in the ninth ward.

49:26.718 --> 49:28.851
So you gotta get to higher ground.

49:32.857 --> 49:35.858
You know that funny little
hill up in Couturie Park?

49:35.893 --> 49:38.286
The one with the little wooden lookout

49:38.406 --> 49:39.878
you gotta climb up to?

49:39.998 --> 49:42.865
Believe it or not, that is the
highest point in New Orleans.

49:42.900 --> 49:45.635
53 feet above sea level.

49:45.670 --> 49:46.890
[Laughs]

49:47.010 --> 49:48.804
Every Sunday morning,

49:48.840 --> 49:52.842
I stand up there, and
I watch the sunrise,

49:52.877 --> 49:55.427
and I count my blessings,

49:56.194 --> 49:57.658
and before you know it,

49:57.778 --> 49:59.815
I feel like I am standing a mile high.

50:01.252 --> 50:02.718
And when you feel a mile high,

50:02.754 --> 50:04.954
anything is possible.

50:07.915 --> 50:09.925
When that bus brought me to Denver,

50:09.961 --> 50:12.071
I really had a hard
time getting on my feet.

50:12.191 --> 50:13.863
It took a while.

50:13.898 --> 50:17.767
You know, so I come
up here every Sunday,

50:17.802 --> 50:19.926
a mile high, on these steps,

50:20.571 --> 50:22.438
and I count my blessings,

50:22.473 --> 50:24.239
and I wait.

50:25.143 --> 50:28.411
Did you ever think about
going back to New Orleans?

50:28.446 --> 50:31.881
This is where I told her I'd be,

50:31.916 --> 50:33.716
and I'm a man of my word.

50:34.712 --> 50:36.710
You know, what if she
got one of my letters,

50:36.830 --> 50:38.929
what if somehow, one of
them got forwarded to her?

50:39.049 --> 50:41.793
You know, what if it
came late, like this one?

50:41.913 --> 50:44.047
What if she comes,

50:44.814 --> 50:46.562
and I'm gone?

50:48.099 --> 50:50.733
Uh... Gabe, um...

50:50.768 --> 50:52.668
The truth is...

50:57.490 --> 51:00.810
I'm not sure how to
tell you this, but...

51:00.845 --> 51:03.345
The truth about Hattie is...

51:05.696 --> 51:07.340
The truth is,

51:07.919 --> 51:10.753
every letter that comes to our office

51:10.788 --> 51:12.664
is a sacred trust,

51:12.784 --> 51:14.724
and we will not rest

51:14.759 --> 51:18.057
until we have used every
means at our disposal

51:18.177 --> 51:19.895
to try and deliver it

51:19.931 --> 51:23.499
to its intended recipient, or, uh...

51:23.534 --> 51:25.101
Or we've determined the whereabouts

51:25.136 --> 51:26.669
of that recipient.

51:26.704 --> 51:28.904
With your permission, of course.

51:30.208 --> 51:32.074
You got it.

51:33.144 --> 51:35.244
I can't promise anything,

51:35.279 --> 51:37.246
but then again, uh...

51:37.281 --> 51:39.081
We are a mile high,

51:39.117 --> 51:41.083
so anything is possible.

51:41.119 --> 51:42.818
<i>[♪♪♪]</i>

51:42.938 --> 51:44.659
Good afternoon, may I speak to someone

51:44.779 --> 51:46.689
regarding disaster relief payments

51:46.724 --> 51:49.291
to victims of hurricane Katrina?

51:49.327 --> 51:50.926
Katrina.

51:50.962 --> 51:52.703
Yes.

51:53.164 --> 51:55.097
Well, might you be able to direct me

51:55.133 --> 51:56.640
to someone who can?

51:56.760 --> 52:00.536
No, no, she was listed as
missing and presumed dead,

52:00.571 --> 52:02.705
we cannot find a death
certificate recorded

52:02.740 --> 52:04.707
with the clerk of Orleans parish...

52:04.742 --> 52:08.511
<i>♪ When I'm with you
feels like heaven... ♪</i>

52:08.546 --> 52:12.294
<i>♪ You're an angel holding me ♪</i>

52:13.918 --> 52:16.689
<i>♪ sweet, sweet lovin' ♪</i>

52:16.809 --> 52:19.284
<i>♪ sets me free... ♪</i>

52:23.026 --> 52:27.753
<i>♪ And in my wildest imagination ♪</i>

52:28.459 --> 52:32.845
<i>♪ I could never never, never imagine ♪</i>

52:34.456 --> 52:39.241
<i>♪ loving me as much as I do you... ♪</i>

52:42.280 --> 52:45.101
So, uh, still no word from Shane?

52:45.221 --> 52:48.842
Not until she's released
from her assignment.

52:49.620 --> 52:51.987
What if... Mr. National Security

52:52.023 --> 52:53.756
isn't interested in releasing her?

52:53.791 --> 52:55.224
Well, considering our last date,

52:55.259 --> 52:58.067
I believe, if she could
come back, she would.

52:58.696 --> 53:00.396
You know, son,

53:00.431 --> 53:03.399
one kiss doesn't make a contract.

53:04.569 --> 53:06.245
But, hey,

53:06.365 --> 53:08.537
what do I know? Kate and I broke up.

53:08.573 --> 53:10.573
Oh, no.

53:10.608 --> 53:12.107
I'm sorry.

53:12.143 --> 53:15.244
She took up with the
fertilizer salesman,

53:15.279 --> 53:17.346
moved to Durango.

53:17.466 --> 53:19.413
There is...

53:19.533 --> 53:22.218
No accounting for taste.

53:22.253 --> 53:23.517
[Chuckling]

53:23.637 --> 53:25.120
Or whatever.

53:25.156 --> 53:27.189
[Laughing]

53:27.225 --> 53:28.858
<i>[♪♪♪]</i>

53:28.893 --> 53:30.760
Right there. You see that?

53:33.798 --> 53:35.231
[Explosion rumbles]

53:35.266 --> 53:37.867
[Warning sirens wail]

53:39.804 --> 53:42.805
<i>[♪♪♪]</i>

53:45.805 --> 53:48.110
- Yes, hello. My name is Oliver...
<i>- Due to the high volume of</i>

53:48.145 --> 53:49.535
<i>calls at the present time,</i>

53:49.655 --> 53:52.815
<i>your waiting time is
approximately 26 minutes.</i>

53:52.850 --> 53:56.002
<i>Thank you for holding. Due
to the high volume of calls... </i>

53:58.589 --> 54:01.062
<i>♪ Well, it may be winter ♪</i>

54:01.659 --> 54:03.950
<i>♪ it may be fall ♪</i>

54:04.629 --> 54:07.630
<i>♪ and I might have plenty ♪</i>

54:07.665 --> 54:10.633
<i>♪ or nothing at all ♪</i>

54:10.668 --> 54:13.736
<i>♪ baby, I'm gonna be there ♪</i>

54:13.771 --> 54:16.105
<i>♪ whenever you call ♪</i>

54:16.140 --> 54:18.741
<i>[♪♪♪]</i>

54:18.776 --> 54:22.778
<i>♪ And every morning ♪</i>

54:22.814 --> 54:26.111
<i>♪ every evening ♪</i>

54:26.231 --> 54:30.119
<i>♪ every day I think of you ♪</i>

54:30.154 --> 54:32.189
<i>[♪♪♪]</i>

54:32.309 --> 54:36.726
<i>♪ The way you loved me
through and through ♪</i>

54:36.761 --> 54:39.546
<i>[♪♪♪]</i>

54:40.598 --> 54:42.164
<i>♪ The way you loved me... ♪</i>

54:42.200 --> 54:45.149
Let us toast next Saturday's
blues night headliner,

54:45.269 --> 54:47.710
the Mailbox Grille presents

54:47.830 --> 54:50.054
the 5280 man himself.

54:50.174 --> 54:51.907
To Gabriel.

54:52.027 --> 54:54.744
- To Gabe.
- [Everyone]: To Gabe.

54:57.281 --> 54:59.114
You guys still looking for Hattie?

54:59.234 --> 55:00.683
We've looked everywhere.

55:00.718 --> 55:03.352
Volunteers of America,
the American Red Cross,

55:03.472 --> 55:06.337
- the Federal Emergency Agency.
- It's very frustrating,

55:06.457 --> 55:08.324
especially since we don't
even know if she's alive.

55:08.359 --> 55:10.526
"Presumed dead" is only a presumption.

55:10.561 --> 55:12.762
Nobody knows exactly how
many were lost in Katrina,

55:12.797 --> 55:15.779
or even where all the
survivors ended up.

55:16.376 --> 55:18.326
Shane would have found a way.

55:19.645 --> 55:21.537
You know, I'm starting
to feel really guilty

55:21.572 --> 55:23.439
about not telling Gabe
what we know about Hattie.

55:23.474 --> 55:25.360
But you don't know anything, right?

55:25.480 --> 55:27.943
Perhaps it's time we told him that.

55:27.979 --> 55:29.783
No man should have to wait forever

55:29.903 --> 55:32.163
for someone who's never going to come.

55:38.256 --> 55:40.656
Uh, excuse me, I'm out. Sorry.

55:46.569 --> 55:48.430
I'm out, too.

56:01.345 --> 56:04.046
[Sighs heavily]

56:09.554 --> 56:11.754
I have a confession to make,

56:11.874 --> 56:15.157
and you can fire me for
it, and I'll understand.

56:15.193 --> 56:17.481
What are you talking about, Norman?

56:19.063 --> 56:22.231
I'm not very good at keeping secrets.

56:22.266 --> 56:24.366
The bad ones hurt my heart.

56:24.402 --> 56:26.202
So...

56:26.237 --> 56:28.938
A few Sundays ago,

56:28.973 --> 56:30.840
I went to the capitol
steps to see Gabe, and...

56:30.875 --> 56:33.458
- And you told him about Hattie?
- I didn't have to tell him.

56:33.578 --> 56:35.578
He kinda figured it out
when he saw my face.

56:35.613 --> 56:37.069
Norman...

56:37.189 --> 56:38.914
He said that deep down inside,

56:38.950 --> 56:42.333
he always suspected that
if Hattie's club was gone,

56:42.453 --> 56:45.221
that probably meant she was, too.

56:45.256 --> 56:48.257
But that wasn't going
to stop him from...

56:48.292 --> 56:51.927
"Keeping the faith," he called it.

56:51.963 --> 56:53.896
And when I left, he
picked up his guitar,

56:53.931 --> 56:56.177
and he started singing again.

56:59.540 --> 57:01.539
You do know,

57:01.659 --> 57:03.873
the definition of insanity

57:03.908 --> 57:06.542
is doing the same thing
over and over again

57:06.577 --> 57:10.079
and expecting a different outcome?

57:10.114 --> 57:11.894
Like...

57:13.600 --> 57:15.818
Waiting for your mother to come back,

57:15.853 --> 57:18.550
and waiting for your
wife to come back, and...

57:19.695 --> 57:22.229
Waiting for Shane to come back?

57:26.597 --> 57:29.064
Maybe standing on those steps is insane.

57:29.100 --> 57:31.321
Maybe it's the only way that Gabe knows

57:31.441 --> 57:33.695
how to keep Hattie alive.

57:35.127 --> 57:36.472
All I know is,

57:36.507 --> 57:37.840
when I walked away,

57:37.875 --> 57:40.099
he was already singing a new song,

57:40.219 --> 57:41.644
and it hit me.

57:43.648 --> 57:45.314
What?

57:45.349 --> 57:48.083
Well, you and I, Oliver,

57:48.119 --> 57:52.755
we have a lot more to hope
for than Gabe does now,

57:52.790 --> 57:54.590
but he's the one out there singing.

58:04.135 --> 58:05.935
[Sighs]

58:07.204 --> 58:09.672
I don't know what to do.

58:15.546 --> 58:17.479
Well, I know what I'm gonna do.

58:18.582 --> 58:20.516
Can you keep a secret?

58:20.551 --> 58:22.651
A good one?

58:26.216 --> 58:28.957
<i>[♪♪♪]</i>

58:30.648 --> 58:33.649
♪ I'm looking out my window ♪

58:33.685 --> 58:36.352
♪ feelin' kinda blue ♪

58:36.387 --> 58:38.721
<i>♪ I ain't heard from my baby ♪</i>

58:38.756 --> 58:41.691
<i>♪ did she find somebody new? ♪</i>

58:41.726 --> 58:43.893
- _
<i>- ♪ So I called up her number ♪</i>

58:43.928 --> 58:48.146
<i>♪ but her number had changed... ♪</i>

58:48.266 --> 58:50.800
Hi. I'm Oliver O'Toole
to see Steve Marek.

58:50.835 --> 58:54.261
<i>♪ And I screamed out her
name and I said "hey" ♪</i>

58:54.381 --> 58:57.874
<i>♪ "hey, hey, hey, oh, my... ♪</i>

58:57.909 --> 58:59.375
I'm sorry.

58:59.410 --> 59:02.111
- He's out of the country.
- Thank you.

59:04.630 --> 59:06.263
Oliver!

59:09.954 --> 59:12.355
I was told you were out of the country.

59:12.390 --> 59:14.734
When you show up without an appointment,

59:14.854 --> 59:16.389
I'm out of the country.

59:17.558 --> 59:19.995
- Where is Shane?
- She's out of the country.

59:21.699 --> 59:23.982
You told me you would keep her safe.

59:24.102 --> 59:25.727
- She's safe.
- How do you know,

59:25.847 --> 59:27.370
if she's out of the country?

59:27.405 --> 59:29.321
Or you are.

59:29.441 --> 59:31.879
Who exactly is in the country right now?

59:31.999 --> 59:34.123
- Okay, look...
- Mr. Marek...

59:34.243 --> 59:35.756
I have an employee

59:35.876 --> 59:38.014
who hasn't reported
to work for three months

59:38.049 --> 59:41.932
with no paperwork to
support her absence.

59:42.052 --> 59:44.575
Unless you can provide
compelling reasons

59:44.695 --> 59:46.502
to the contrary, I would like
my employee back now.

59:46.622 --> 59:48.475
You can't have her back,
she's critical to the mission.

59:48.595 --> 59:50.729
- Oh, I'll bet she is.
- Listen, Oliver,

59:50.849 --> 59:53.627
- I understand your situation...
- No, you don't.

59:55.760 --> 59:58.928
And that situation has changed.

01:00:14.152 --> 01:00:15.952
We were out of the country.

01:00:15.987 --> 01:00:18.421
We had to turn in our laptops,

01:00:18.456 --> 01:00:20.972
and tablets, and phones.
We couldn't carry anything

01:00:21.092 --> 01:00:23.895
that could be tracked, or
hacked, or compromised.

01:00:24.015 --> 01:00:25.728
There are means

01:00:26.589 --> 01:00:29.100
by which you could have contacted us

01:00:29.220 --> 01:00:31.133
while still maintaining privacy.

01:00:31.169 --> 01:00:32.827
A postcard. A letter. A burner phone...

01:00:32.947 --> 01:00:36.264
The point is that I still would
have been breaking the rules,

01:00:36.384 --> 01:00:38.082
and you, of all people, should...

01:00:38.202 --> 01:00:41.243
Wait, how do you know
about burner phones?

01:00:41.279 --> 01:00:43.514
Sometimes, we watch

01:00:43.634 --> 01:00:45.915
action movies on poker night.

01:00:46.448 --> 01:00:47.850
Poker night?

01:00:47.885 --> 01:00:49.618
Action... Who's "we"?

01:00:49.654 --> 01:00:51.128
Norman, Rita,

01:00:51.248 --> 01:00:52.521
my dad,

01:00:53.064 --> 01:00:54.290
Ramon.

01:00:54.325 --> 01:00:57.960
[Laughs] I would give
anything to see that.

01:00:57.996 --> 01:00:59.651
Apparently not.

01:01:03.234 --> 01:01:04.633
Oliver,

01:01:05.291 --> 01:01:08.107
what I am doing here right now

01:01:08.227 --> 01:01:10.039
is really important.

01:01:10.074 --> 01:01:12.308
And there's still work
that needs to be done.

01:01:12.657 --> 01:01:15.412
- Are you sure?
- That's what Steve says.

01:01:15.532 --> 01:01:18.180
Well, then it must be true.

01:01:20.685 --> 01:01:22.935
Do you really think that if
I could go back to Denver,

01:01:23.055 --> 01:01:26.455
I would spend one more minute here?

01:01:26.491 --> 01:01:28.712
I don't know about having a chance,

01:01:28.832 --> 01:01:32.361
but I know you have a choice.

01:01:36.067 --> 01:01:37.833
Can we change the subject, please?

01:01:37.869 --> 01:01:39.702
[Sighs]

01:01:41.780 --> 01:01:43.706
Did you find Gabe?

01:01:43.741 --> 01:01:46.412
I promised I would, and we did.

01:01:46.532 --> 01:01:49.541
That's great, because I
have news about Hattie.

01:01:50.091 --> 01:01:53.382
I couldn't stop thinking about
her, so every chance I had,

01:01:53.502 --> 01:01:55.636
I would run a new search
for old tax records,

01:01:55.756 --> 01:01:57.498
or old employment records,

01:01:57.510 --> 01:01:59.555
anything that I could
think of, really, and...

01:02:00.154 --> 01:02:01.424
I found something.

01:02:02.527 --> 01:02:04.817
- And... ?
- I think she's alive.

01:02:04.937 --> 01:02:07.430
An A.G. Hatfield spent three
days trapped in the Superdome,

01:02:07.465 --> 01:02:10.081
and then evacuated to
Houston, which is probably why

01:02:10.201 --> 01:02:12.077
she dropped off the rolls in Louisiana.

01:02:12.197 --> 01:02:15.320
Now, from what I can tell, if it is her,

01:02:16.156 --> 01:02:18.958
it seems that she started
over again in Austin.

01:02:19.544 --> 01:02:21.701
I only have a street address,

01:02:21.821 --> 01:02:23.746
but no number.

01:02:24.289 --> 01:02:27.385
I was gonna follow up
when this was all over,

01:02:27.505 --> 01:02:30.186
but now that you're here...

01:02:33.404 --> 01:02:36.392
I hope she was worth waiting for.

01:02:38.850 --> 01:02:40.996
So do I.

01:02:47.772 --> 01:02:49.357
[Cell phone ringtone chimes]

01:02:54.745 --> 01:02:56.306
No cellphones,

01:02:56.854 --> 01:02:58.584
no contact, hmm.

01:02:58.704 --> 01:03:01.327
Oliver, it's a dedicated
phone just for...

01:03:01.447 --> 01:03:03.153
I'm sorry.

01:03:09.299 --> 01:03:11.093
I have to get back.

01:03:11.129 --> 01:03:12.294
Of course.

01:03:13.076 --> 01:03:14.908
You have no choice.

01:03:15.274 --> 01:03:16.565
Oliver...

01:03:16.601 --> 01:03:18.300
I would like my pen back, please.

01:03:21.005 --> 01:03:23.770
Of course. I mean, I was
going to give it back

01:03:23.890 --> 01:03:26.497
- when I came...
- Goodbye, Ms. McInerney.

01:03:34.418 --> 01:03:36.257
What would you say

01:03:36.377 --> 01:03:38.687
if I had a friend, here in Washington,

01:03:38.722 --> 01:03:40.802
a highly-placed official with the USPS

01:03:40.922 --> 01:03:42.858
Division of Cyber Security

01:03:42.893 --> 01:03:45.905
who informed me that the crisis
which occurred three months ago

01:03:46.025 --> 01:03:48.163
was resolved over three weeks ago,

01:03:48.198 --> 01:03:50.225
and that the release of all

01:03:50.345 --> 01:03:52.649
emergency consulting assets,

01:03:52.769 --> 01:03:54.369
such as yourself

01:03:54.405 --> 01:03:57.386
was at the sole discretion
of your team leader?

01:03:59.702 --> 01:04:01.737
If that were true,

01:04:02.529 --> 01:04:04.513
Steve would let me go home.

01:04:04.548 --> 01:04:06.048
Why would a man

01:04:06.083 --> 01:04:09.518
who obviously cares so much about you

01:04:09.553 --> 01:04:12.220
let you go if he didn't have to?

01:04:14.124 --> 01:04:17.897
I ask myself that all the time.

01:04:22.333 --> 01:04:24.553
I made that part up,

01:04:27.004 --> 01:04:28.704
about the highly-placed official.

01:04:28.739 --> 01:04:30.539
I know.

01:04:33.802 --> 01:04:36.531
- It was a pretty good bluff, though.
- Right.

01:04:37.445 --> 01:04:39.784
- I learned it playing poker.
- [Chuckles]

01:04:42.453 --> 01:04:45.420
But I can't lie to you.

01:04:47.399 --> 01:04:49.124
I know.

01:04:51.224 --> 01:04:54.229
I'm just wondering if Steve can.

01:05:07.811 --> 01:05:09.570
<i>Tell me the truth.</i>

01:05:09.690 --> 01:05:12.581
Am I here because you need
me, or because you want me?

01:05:12.616 --> 01:05:14.182
What kind of a guy flies
all the way down here,

01:05:14.218 --> 01:05:15.984
and then leaves without
getting what he came for?

01:05:16.020 --> 01:05:19.254
The kind of man that lets
me make up my own mind,

01:05:19.289 --> 01:05:21.957
but I can't do that unless
I have all the facts.

01:05:21.992 --> 01:05:23.458
Okay.

01:05:23.494 --> 01:05:25.293
The crisis is over.

01:05:25.329 --> 01:05:27.998
I could shut down your
part of the operation,

01:05:28.118 --> 01:05:29.738
but I don't want to.

01:05:29.858 --> 01:05:32.968
For security reasons and
for personal reasons.

01:05:34.339 --> 01:05:35.838
What?

01:05:35.850 --> 01:05:37.539
Do you really think

01:05:37.574 --> 01:05:39.474
that delivering old letters

01:05:39.510 --> 01:05:42.344
is as important as some of
the world-changing stuff

01:05:42.379 --> 01:05:44.513
that we do here every day?

01:05:44.548 --> 01:05:46.181
Are you really telling me

01:05:46.216 --> 01:05:47.872
you want to throw all that away

01:05:47.992 --> 01:05:50.355
for a squeaky porch swing in Denver?

01:05:53.316 --> 01:05:55.824
- [Sighs heavily]
- You wanna know the truth?

01:05:55.859 --> 01:05:57.048
Please.

01:06:02.566 --> 01:06:05.167
I'm still in love with you.

01:06:10.144 --> 01:06:12.059
_

01:06:12.179 --> 01:06:14.140
Welcome to Texas.

01:06:21.581 --> 01:06:23.822
Pardon me, is this, uh, Hattie's place?

01:06:23.942 --> 01:06:25.720
Well, that depends.

01:06:26.098 --> 01:06:28.449
I'm Hattie, and this is my place.

01:06:28.569 --> 01:06:30.195
[Sighs] I'm Oliver O'Toole,

01:06:30.315 --> 01:06:32.329
and I'm from the United
States Postal Service,

01:06:32.449 --> 01:06:34.144
and I have a letter for you

01:06:34.264 --> 01:06:36.727
that's taken a long time to deliver,

01:06:36.847 --> 01:06:38.096
I'm afraid.

01:06:39.266 --> 01:06:41.065
I hope you remember him, because he

01:06:41.185 --> 01:06:42.844
certainly remembers you.

01:06:42.964 --> 01:06:44.369
Oh, my Lord.

01:06:45.047 --> 01:06:46.471
Now...

01:06:46.506 --> 01:06:48.873
Are you telling me he's still alive?

01:06:51.811 --> 01:06:55.246
<i>[♪♪♪]</i>

